h1      3. Git Branching
H2      3.1.	Branching in a Nutshell.
div(id="31")
  p    Branching means you diverge from the main line of development
  p    and continue to do work without messing with that main line.
  h3    Branching in a Nutshell
  p    When you make a commit, Git stores a commit object that
  p    contains a pointer to the snapshot of the content you staged.
  h3    Creating a New Branch
  p    [$ git branch [branch name]]
  p    How does Git know what branch you’re currently on?
  p    It keeps a special pointer called HEAD.
  p    Note that this is a lot different than the concept of HEAD
  p    in other VCSs you may be used to, such as Subversion or CVS.
  p    The git branch command only created a new branch – it didn’t switch to that branch.
  br
  p    To see where the point of your HEAD, use:
  p    [$ git log --oneline --decorate]
  p    [$ git checkout [branch name]
  p    That command did two things.
  p    It moved the HEAD pointer back to point to the [branch name] branch,
  p    and it reverted the files in your working directory
  p    back to the snapshot that master points to.
  p    [git log --oneline --decorate --graph --all]
