h1      5. Distributed Git
H2      5.1. Distributed Workflows
div(id="51")
  h3    Distributed Workflows
  p    Unlike another centralized VCS, GIT allows every developer to be
  p    on both a node and a hub states.
  p    So lets cover a few common paradigms of workflow:
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Distributed-Workflows#Centralized-Workflow") Centralized Workflow
  p
    img(src="http://www.shaney.net/git/images/centralized.png").img-fluid
  p    One central hub, or repository, can accept code, and everyone synchronizes their work to it.
  p    This is also not limited to small teams.

  hr
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Distributed-Workflows#Integration-Manager-Workflow") Integration-Manager Workflow
  p
    img(src="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/book/05-distributed-git/images/integration-manager.png").img-fluid
  p
  p    Because Git allows you to have multiple remote repositories,
  p    it’s possible to have a workflow where each developer
  p    has write access to their own public repository and read access to everyone else’s.
  p    The process works as follows:
  p
    ol
      li The project maintainer pushes to their public repository.
      li  A contributor clones that repository and makes changes.
      li  The contributor pushes to their own public copy.
      li  The contributor sends the maintainer an e-mail asking them to pull changes.
      li  The maintainer aps the contributor’s repo as a remote and merges locally.
      li  The maintainer pushes merged changes to the main repository.

  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Distributed-Workflows#Dictator-and-Lieutenants-Workflow") Dictator and Lieutenants Workflow
  p
    img(src="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/book/05-distributed-git/images/benevolent-dictator.png").img-fluid

  p    This is a variant of a multiple-repository workflow.
  p    It’s generally used by huge projects with hundreds of collaborators;
  p    Various integration managers are in charge of certain parts of the repository;
  p    they’re called lieutenants.
  p    All the lieutenants have one integration manager known as the benevolent dictator.
  p    The process works like this:
    ol
      li Regular developers work on their topic branch and rebase their work on top of master. The master branch is that of the dictator.
      li Lieutenants merge the developers’ topic branches into their master branch.
      li The dictator merges the lieutenants’ master branches into the dictator’s master branch.
      li The dictator pushes their master to the reference repository so the other developers can rebase on it.
h2    5.2. Contributing to a Project
div(id="52")
  h3    Contributing to a Project
  p    The main difficulty with describing how to contribute to a project
  p    is that there are a huge number of variations on how it’s done.
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Contributing-to-a-Project#Commit-Guidelines").
        Commit Guidelines
  p    Before we start looking at the specific use cases, here’s a quick note about commit messages.
  p    First, you don’t want to submit any whitespace errors.
  p    Before you commit, run [$ git diff --check] -
  p    It is identifies possible whitespace errors and lists them for you.
  p    Next, try to make each commit a logically separate changeset.
  p    If you can, try to make your changes digestible – don’t code for a whole weekend on five different issues
  p    and then submit them all as one massive commit on Monday.
  p    The last thing to keep in mind is the commit message.
  p    Here is a template originally written by Tim Pope:

  p
    blockquote.text-whitespaces.
      Short (50 chars or less) summary of changes

      More detailed explanatory text, if necessary.  Wrap it to
      about 72 characters or so.  In some contexts, the first
      line is treated as the subject of an email and the rest of
      the text as the body.  The blank line separating the
      summary from the body is critical (unless you omit the body
      entirely); tools like rebase can get confused if you run
      the two together.

      Further paragraphs come after blank lines.

        - Bullet points are okay, too

        - Typically a hyphen or asterisk is used for the bullet,
        preceded by a single space, with blank lines in
        between, but conventions vary here
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Contributing-to-a-Project#Private-Small-Team").
        Private Small Team
