  p    meantime as this doing another developers,
  p    you need fetch remote changes and then merge with your.
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Contributing-to-a-Project#Private-Managed-Team").
        Private Managed Team
  p    The ability of smaller subgroups of a team to collaborate via
  p    remote branches without necessarily having to
  p    involve or impede the entire team is a huge benefit of Git.
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Contributing-to-a-Project#Forked-Public-Project").
        Forked Public Project
  p    [$ git merge --no-commit --squash]
  p    The --squash option takes all the work on the merged branch
  p    and squashes it into one non-merge commit on top of the branch you’re on.
  h3
