  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Revision-Selection").
        Revision Selection
  p    Git allows you to specify specific commits or a range of commits in several ways.
  p    They aren’t necessarily obvious but are helpful to know.

  h3    Single Revisions
  p    You can obviously refer to a commit by the SHA-1 hash that it’s given,
  p    but there are more human-friendly ways to refer to commits as well.
  p    This section outlines the various ways you can refer to a single commit.

  h3    Short SHA-1
  p    Git can enough precisely to figure out what you had meant if
  p    your partial SHA-1 commit is typed at leas 4 characters and unambiguous.
  p    For example, the following commands are equivalent:
  p    [$ git show 1c002p4b536e7479fe34593e72e6c6c1819e53b ]
  p    [$ git show 1c002p4b536e7479f                       ]
  p    [$ git show 1c002d                                   ]
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Revision-Selection#Branch-References").
        Branch References
  p    You can use a name branch in any GIT command that expects a commit object or SHA-1 value.
  p    Specific SHA-1 points of any branch you can take with plumbing tool called [rev-parse].
  p    More info
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/ch10/_git_internals")   see here.

  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Revision-Selection#RefLog-Shortnames").
        RefLog Shortnames
  p    While you are in workflow Git automatically keeps a "reflog" -
  p    log of where your HEAD and branch refs have been for the last few month.
  p    You can see thats with [$ git reflog] command.
  p    And you can specify older commits use @{n} reference that you see in the reflog output.
  p    You can also use this syntax to see where a branch was some specific amount of time ago:
  p    [$ git show master@{yesterday}]
  p    To see reflog information formatted like the git log output: [$ git log -g]
  p    All reflogs strictly local and after you clone a repo, you'll get an empty reflog.


  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Revision-Selection#Ancestry-References").
        Ancestry References
  p    If you place "^" at the end of a reference (branch, HEAD, SHA-1), Git resolves it to means "the parent of that commit".
  p    Or if you pace "^n", GIT resolves it to means "N parent of reference".
  p    The other main ancestry specification is the "~".
  p    If "~" just plased at end ref, it equivalent "^".
  p    If you specify a number, "~2" it'll means "the first parent of the first parent"
  p    - it traverses the first parents the number of times you specify.
  p    You can also written something like "HEAD^^^" or (equivalent) "HEAD~3", or combine them "HEAD~3^2" and so on.

  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Revision-Selection#Commit-Ranges").
        Commit Ranges
  p    Now that you can specify individual commits, let’s see how to specify ranges of commits.

  h3    Double Dot
  p    [$ git log [refA]..[refB]]
  p    This basically asks Git to resolve a range of commits that
  p    are reachable from one commit but aren’t reachable from another.
  p    If the last ref unspecified - GIT substitutes its with HEAD.

  h3    Multiple Points
  p    If you want to specify more than two branches to indicate your revision
  p    Git allows you to do this by using either the ^ character or
  p    --not before any reference from which you don’t want to see reachable commits.
  p    Thus these three commands are equivalent:
  p    [$ git log refA..refB ]
  p    [$ git log ^refA refB ]
  p    [$ git log refB --not refA ]

  h3    Triple Dot
  p    [[$ git log [refA]...[refB]]]
  p    This syntax specifies all the commtis that are not common of two refs.
  p    You can also use the [--left-right] switch,
  p    which shows you which side of the range each commit is in.
