  p
  h3(title="(--soft)").
        Step 1: Move HEAD (--soft)
  p    This isn’t the same as changing HEAD itself (which is what checkout does)
  p    reset moves the branch that HEAD is pointing to.

  h3(title="the Index (--mixed)").
        Step 2: Updating the Index (--mixed)
  p    This is the default option wher you run reset command.
  p    The next thing reset will do is to update the Index
  p    with the contents of whatever snapshot HEAD now points to.

  h3(title="the Working Directory (--hard)").
        Step 3: Updating the Working Directory (--hard)
  p    The third thing that reset will do
  p    is to make the Working Directory look like the Index.
  p    We could back our last commit with [$ git reflog] command.

  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Reset-Demystified#Reset-With-a-Path").
        Reset With a Path
  p    [$ git reset [path to file]] where
  p    is the just shortand for [$ git reset --mixed HEAD file.txt]
  p    So it essentially just copies file.txt from HEAD to the Index.
  p    This has the practical effect of unstaging the file.
  h3
    a(href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Tools-Reset-Demystified#Squashing").
